{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512681"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11936"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11936"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.15,0.72,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96409"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4532"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79058"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1207"},{"type":"tags","id":"1705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42688"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96409"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department. Due to a language barrier, he is unable to provide a detailed history. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His left eye is severely bruised and swollen shut. He has significant localised tenderness on palpation over the infraorbital rim. The doctor is able to open his eyes for further examination. His visual acuity is normal and his pupils are equal and reactive to light. On testing of extraocular eye movements, he is unable to look upward with the affected eye and complains of pain on doing so. Additionally, there is apparent discomfort on downward gaze. Fundoscopic examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Orbital cellulitis","Periorbital haematoma","Orbital floor fracture","Retrobulbar haemorrhage","Maxillary sinus fracture"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is most likely suffering from an \u003Cstrong\u003Eorbital fracture\u003C/strong\u003E of the inferior wall. Despite the language barrier preventing a detailed history, the clinical examination provides strong evidence for this diagnosis. The localised tenderness on palpation of the infraorbital rim is highly suggestive of a \u0027step off\u0027 sign of a fracture. The restricted upward eye movement resulting in pain is indicative of entrapment of the inferior rectus muscle, which is a common complication of inferior orbital blowout fractures. Patients may complain of diplopia on vertical eye movements. This diagnosis can be confirmed via a CT orbit. In cases of entrapment or restriction of the inferior rectus muscle, the eye is \u0027tethered\u0027 and unable to move in the opposite direction, ie: elevation. This is in contrast to when there is paresis in the muscle which will only affect the action of the involved muscle. For example, paresis of the inferior rectus would lead to a deficit in downward gaze whereases a mechanical entrapment or restriction of the muscle would lead to a deficit in upward gaze. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrbital cellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, proptosis, and limitation of eye movements in all directions. While this patient has limited eye movement, the lack of systemic symptoms and erythema make orbital cellulitis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eperiorbital haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the bruising and swelling, but it would not account for the specific limitation in upward gaze. Periorbital haematomas are often seen in conjunction with orbital fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetrobulbar haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious complication of orbital trauma that can lead to vision loss if not promptly treated. However, it typically presents with proptosis, increased intraocular pressure, and pain with eye movements in all directions. The specific limitation in upward gaze are more consistent with an orbital floor fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emaxillary sinus fracture\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in conjunction with an orbital floor fracture, but alone it would not explain the specific eye movement limitations observed in this patient. The maxillary sinus lies below the orbit, and while its fracture can affect the orbital floor, it typically doesn\u0027t result in the specific upward gaze limitation seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that even with normal examination findings, patients with suspected orbital fractures should be considered for specialist referral to an ophthalmologist for repeat examination to exclude other traumatic injuries such as retinal detachment or occult globe rupture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Orbital blowout fractures should be suspected in blunt force trauma directly to the eye.","Inferior orbital blowout fractures can result in entrapment of the inferior rectus muscle."],"references":["Weaver CS, Knoop KJ. Ophthalmic trauma. In: Knoop KJ, Stack LB, Storrow AB, et al, eds. The Atlas of Emergency Medicine. 4th ed. McGraw-Hill.","Boyette JR, Pemberton JD, Bonilla-Velez J. Management of orbital fractures: challenges and solutions. Clin Ophthalmol. 2015 Nov 17;9:2127-37. doi: 10.2147/OPTH.S80463. PMID: 26604678; PMCID: PMC4655944."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79058"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11936"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79058"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T11:23:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T14:02:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4532"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96409"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attri